As a person who never been in Gainesville, my first instinct was to look through recommended options online. If you look through top recommended food locations in a small town like Gville, Sababa is always mentioned on any list. I have decided to give it a try. Located in the downtown area, the location is very small. They have space where you can order food and a couple of tables and chairs where you can dine in. Based on the condition the restaurant is at and the old pictures of regulars that date back to 2015, the location is pretty old. The menu is might be a bit hard to understand for customers who are not familiar with vegetarian food and not sure what to order. For my order, I got falafel pita and shakshuka. You have a choice of a meal or a pita sandwich. I would recommend going for a meal. It comes with Israeli couscous, pickled red cabbage, some veggies & chickpeas a cup of tahini sauce, and homemade hummus. The food itself was delicious, the combination of all flavors together was incredible. After eating the meal you feel so wholesome. You also get a couple of warm pita bread with your order. After trying a couple of places in Gville, Sababa beats all of them for me. Very simple dishes that make you feel good about eating out! My only recommendation to a manager or an owner of this location is to improve on a condition of the restaurant itself.

Not what I expected. Our family went on a road trip to Panama Beach, on our way we found Sababa. As a family that really loves Mediterranean cuisine and Israeli food in particular, we were very excited to add a stop in Gainesville. Once we arrived to the place the immediate feeling was to leave. It looks like an old Jewish place taken from the mid 50s. And not in a good way. It did not look very clean to us and the dining area is poor and uncomfortable. The food...well the Hummus was bad...heartburn bad, the falafel was good and the tahini with the Israeli salad in a pita was ok. But ok is not what we expected. The pita bread was underwhelming. The kids had the schnitzel sandwich and again...nothing to get excited over. While we made a choice to stay and eat, and while the girl at the front was extra nice, and while none of us had "bad business" in the bathroom after the meal...our family all agreed not to return to Sababa...ever... In short our Sababa meal was more of a Ba'asa one.

Description: I don't know too much about the history of Sababa, but I was told it used to be at the UF Hillel before recently moving in downtown. A few doors away from Maude's, Sababa is a relatively straightforward and simple restaurant.  Food & Service: Space inside is limited but they do have a few tables outside you can sit at. Not really a problem unless you're trying to bring a big group of friends there to eat. The menu is handwritten on a big black board with lots of options to choose from. I scanned Yelp before coming and decide to get the falafel platter. I probably won't get the platter again but it was very reasonable for the price. The staff was very friendly and seemed to enjoy their new location. The enthusiasm could even be felt from the older lady that worked there (maybe a grandparent or mother?).  The food came out pretty quick. Like other reviewers have pointed out, the falafel was really well made. Side tip, you definitely want to eat them quickly while they're still hot though! The pickled cucumbers were a nice addition and the salad was very subtle but refreshing. I wasn't a big fan of the other side items as much but that could just be personal preference. The hummus and pita bread were solid. The couscous on the side was light but had a nice subtle flavor to it!  Final Thoughts: All in all, it was a quaint experience to say the least. I'll be honest and say it's not my preferred type of food but they definitely know what they're doing. I will probably be back to try the Schnitzel and Shawarma soon!

In only one occasion they were not out of the Veggie Schnitzel, which leaves you with the falafel as the only option. Luckily, the falafel plate is delicious, so it's worth going there if that's what you are looking for. We keep visiting the restaurant and hoping for more options or at least for the the shawarma to be available, but we have not been that lucky yet.  In summary, this is a local business with good vibe but poor organization which would not be anybody's business if it didn't impact the quality of service as it does. We want a local business with good people to thrive, but we are not going to continue visiting a restaurant that offers such few options for vegans or vegetarians.
